European inflation slipped in food
The accelerated inflation, registered in the euro area, is due in the first place to the dizzying growth in the price of food products.
The increase in prices in the month of November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro zone, registering - after the 2.6 percent in the month of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Union Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only gave 3 percent as probable - Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the North American, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, together with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause an inflation spiral.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to, two percent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: &quot;you have to negotiate&quot; on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, registered in Germany, broke the twelve-year record; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation soared in the euro zone as a result of skyrocketing food and energy prices.
Wheat term prices increased by 88 percent and soybean prices also reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, with the black gold already reaching almost 100 dollars a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while for 2009 it will drop to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain around 3 percent for the next 3 or 4 months, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup foresees a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December support for the Alliance of Young Democrats rose significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while Gallup had never before experienced such a low level - 13 percent - for the socialists.
The difference in the case of the secure voters of the parties - due to the greater firmness of the opposition voters - would mean a support of more than two thirds (71 percent) compared to the support of one fifth for the Socialists ( 20 percent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not even reach the necessary limit to have a parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the safe voters there are one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous low point - it has never been higher, with 41 percent finding the country&#39;s economic situation particularly bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation it&#39;s pretty bad.
Families, after the more hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about the change in their own economic situation.
As regards next year, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate and only a tenth expect an improvement.
In the month of December, 71 percent of those consulted, a figure higher than any previous Gallup survey, estimated that the Prime Minister performs his duties more badly than well.
13 percent of those consulted trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány a lot, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of those consulted.
54 percent of the population does not trust the Head of Government at all and 27 percent does not trust the president of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is what proportion of society thinks that it is possible to control the discontent experienced with the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
Whereas after the riots in October last year, 35 percent considered that it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, today this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority ( 33 percent) believe that the only solution is to hold new elections.
The interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of those surveyed to the question about participation answered that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said that it is probable that they will participate.
By way of comparison, in &quot;general elections to be held this Sunday&quot; only 55 percent of the population would safely participate and another 15 percent believe their participation is probable. Based on the current intentions of the voters, there is no doubt about the result of the referendum.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of paying for study fees, 79 percent for the medical consultation service, and 84 percent for hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of the voters would reject the introduction of study rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is Auchan, Tesco has quintupled its prices
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs gold business triangle maintained the average increase in the price level of 16 percent, with the difference that this year VAT was not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year the usual Christmas basket of the newspaper Napi also increased by an average of 16 percent in the Budaörs gold trading triangle, but growth was well above HUF thousand in all hypermarkets.
As in December of last year, prices in food supermarkets had already &quot;shot up&quot;, so there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below HUF 9,000, today they cannot buy for even HUF 10,000.
The Napi basket in the studied hypermarkets exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF by at least HUF 91.
And the basket with the highest value was 10,573 HUF.
(In the year 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a strong increase in turkey breast fillet, walnuts and poppy seeds.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data from the Central Statistical Office, although in Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of Coke with a redeemable two-liter bottle was less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, was only 257 HUF.
Still, in Napi Auchan&#39;s basket she was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
By our calculations, compared to last year&#39;s Christmas prices, Cora was up 15 per cent, while Tesco and Auchan were up about 18 per cent on Napi&#39;s basket prices.
Comparing the values of the most expensive basket of last year with that of the cheapest basket of this year, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between the cheapest of last year and the most expensive of this year It&#39;s been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average growth in prices was 1206 HUF, so that during Christmas last year the VAT increase was felt in prices.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade, supermarkets were visibly incapable of making a decision on the price margin to apply for each product and calculating the effect of price changes on consumption.
(If the retailer misplans the velocity of a product&#39;s circulation, he or she may miss out on a significant margin profit that adjusts for sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the VAT increase, that the most expensive was 1,720 HUF higher than the value registered in 2006, while the difference in the cheapest was only 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest one also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, a catastrophic growth in prices was recorded in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of basic consumer items grew by more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Statistics Office: this office, in the case of some staple foods, registered a price increase of more than 30 percent in the 12-month interval.
Thus, for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of eggs.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, since in the price of this product, which was already quite expensive last year compared to the base, only 10 percent was registered, in the worst case. of price increase.
By all accounts, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose drastic price increases even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain about the golden trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, the majority of consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
They buy large quantities of all products, taking preserved food by pallet.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed in front of the checkouts at all three stores because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country the sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to the survey institutes because the income is below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in that of household appliances.
In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been registered in hospitals, caused primarily by the improper application of antibiotics.
The hygienic circumstances prevailing in hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds and the overload of the staff do not favor the control of the infections - affirms the doctor-head of the department of the National Center of Epidemiology.
In many hospitals you save even with disinfectants.
Not long ago a MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
An injured person from a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital shortly after as a result of being infected with MRSA and since then it has not been possible to perform a major surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body .
Until December 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multiresistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System - said Karolina Böröcz, physician-head of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that this amount of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has been registered in hospitals, there is no information on the rest.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, that is to say Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One third of human beings carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (eg, sore throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easily treated.
However, once antibiotics are excessively or improperly applied, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics become highly resistant to antibiotics and are rapidly contagious under inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, for example wound infections or sepsis, primarily in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with weakened organisms, in the elderly or in low-weight persons.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about the MRSA infection, these infections are commonplace in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
antibiotic resistant
&quot;These patients are isolated, nurses attend them in rubber gloves and a mask and there are adequate antibiotics for their treatment&quot; - said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their bodies, but even then infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital-acquired MRSA infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances are not conducive to preventing the formation and transmission of multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA in their bodies.
However, in Hungarian hospitals the taking of microbiological samples is not fashionable.
This fact is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when visible MRSA infections in the patient already occur - said the doctor-head of department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict orders for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
It is necessary to insist that antibiotic therapy be directed, that is, microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent the development of resistance to drugs, but hospitals do not always comply with this requirement.
Taking microbiological samples is even less frequent in the case of ambulatory patients or in primary care - stated Karolina Böröcz.
Save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, however considerable shortcomings are also experienced in hospitals in this regard.
MRSA is spread through droplet transmission and direct contact between people; however, in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
What&#39;s more, hospital wards are often crowded, beds are often close together, although in order to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, one can also experience - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals with a less favorable economic situation, savings are made with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater chance of infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where the appropriate prevention measures are followed, fewer infections of this type are registered or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, which is why it is fought in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and that of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
