400 million euros more for infrastructures
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice-President Marta Gajecka signed three credit limit agreements on Friday in Budapest for a total value of 400 million euros to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of 300 million euros to finance transport and environmental protection projects in the Hungarian budget, which will be carried out from the subsidy of the cohesion funds, of which the parties had previously signed a credit agreement for a value of 100 million, the contract they have just signed refers to the use of the remaining 200 million euros.
The credit contract of 150 million euros is also used to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of 300 million euros for this objective in Hungary, on the use of the remaining 150 million euros the decision will be made later, when extending the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will use mainly for the innovations and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the conversations they also covered the issue of the construction of the 4th line of the Metro.
An agreement was reached that by the time Hungary finalizes the details of the Metro financing with the EU, they will return to the issue of whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do it.
According to János Veres, this could take place as early as the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth €8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is adjusted to EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging a commission for keeping the loan available to the debtor.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of the whole of Europe is directed towards that previously little mentioned Balkan country.
What, where and who buys on the even cheaper EU market, which will quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap apartments on the ski slopes and chalets on the beaches.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the beaches Albena, the &quot;Golden Coast&quot;, the &quot;Sun Coast&quot;, the old Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for real estate also in the environs of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy real estate in the particularly cheap area of Rus.
