The ministers of the government of the Czech Republic signed yesterday with representatives of the European Commission a total of nine operational programs from which the Czech Republic can get 14 billion euros (approximately 365 billion crowns).
This is practically half of the total sum that the Czech Republic can obtain from Brussels for the years 2007 to 2013.
Approximately SEK 125 billion will come out of seven operational programs for the regions.
Czech companies will be able to get about SEK 100 billion from the Enterprise and Innovation Program.
Most of the money will go to transport, up to 150 billion.
The Transport Program is the largest of the operational programs and represents up to 22 percent of the resources that the Czech Republic can get from the fund.
This money increases the budget of the state fund for transport infrastructure that next year will have the amount of 90.8 billion crowns.
The Business and Innovation program should serve entrepreneurs and companies to obtain resources for business innovation.
Companies should get funding for the acquisition of new technologies, for industrial research and for the implementation of more effective organizational methods.
When it comes to the current use of EU funds, the Czech Republic is among the newcomers that use them the least.
