Banks want to solve the crisis
The American Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian Central Banks decided to fight together against the financial market crisis.
In the Monetary Market, more than one hundred billion dollars will be received through bidding.
In these tenders, banks auction the interest rates for which they are able to lend money.
For example, the American Fed will send forty billion dollars to bid, and then another twenty-four billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the attacks of September 11, it is the first time that central banks of different states agree on this coordinated process to protect and reduce the consequences of the financial crisis.
&quot;This step should solve the biggest economic problem, namely the ever-growing scarcity of free capital that banks could lend,&quot; Bernard Baumohl of the Economic Outlook Group, a consulting firm, wrote in his report for clients.
&quot;This coordinated action by central banks probably lowered the recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent,&quot; Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent $60 billion on bad loans, mostly in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
&quot;Central banks must really be afraid of what awaits them still when they decided to take this step,&quot; said ABN Amro chief economist Kieran Davies.
&quot;It seems that the situation is really bad,&quot; he added.
The central banks fear that they have the same problems of access to loans and that for this reason they will have to lend more expensive to their clients.
This would reduce consumption and send the US economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the world economy.
The central banks thus decided, after they failed to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used for lending money in the interbank market.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to lend money even as the Central Banks of the US, Canada and Britain cut their interest rates several times in the autumn.
&quot;It will have the same effect as another drop in interest rates,&quot; Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
