After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Bad Arolsen Nazi archives, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
Until now, the 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were only available for &quot;humanitarian&quot; purposes, that is to say individually and by name, at the request of a former victim or of their successors.
The eleven States in charge of its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them up to researchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening is effective as of yesterday.
sensitive information
Historians&#39; access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to search &quot;particularly on the movements of the prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of the forced workers&quot;, explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, were opposed to opening these registered documents to the public, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the supposed homosexuality or the mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the deported or forced compatriots and, eventually, provide them with proof of their internment. in order to open the way to their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
&quot;There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents,&quot; Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Center on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität in Berlin, had declared in 2006.
