England takes to court the demands of Owais Shah and Ravi Bopara
Here are two dilemmas, each as difficult as the other.
Who should beat the No.6 for England in Kandy this weekend, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, none the less in the face of the first test against Sri Lanka, who should make the decision?
The second question is relevant because David Graveney, the president of the team that is on loan - with that particular title at least - is here to help Peter Moores, the manager, and Michael Vaughan, the captain, to decide; and also because the desk of Hugh Morris, director of England, is beginning to fill up with offers to become a national selector, and if not, a part-time one.
The one who does not get the sixth place bat will be unfortunate, but life is often unfair and so is sport.
It is not easy to throw away what a man at the top of his profession does, while another never gets beyond the bottom level, sometimes through lack of luck rather than ability.
Not only in cricket the choice is difficult, because judgments are required that always end up being subjective.
Is it the right time for Bopara to rise up?
Is it fair to Shah if he does it?
The same question could be asked in another respect if, says John Edwards or &quot;Tubby&quot; Banerjee, two bright young executives with good degrees and who know the business well, were to be promoted to the board: there&#39;s only room for one of them.
Who is to say what is a good standard for a cricketer, unless he is given the next chance to sink or swim?
Figures naturally have a great influence on decisions, but they also have opportunities.
Within a team, a cricketer has to catch the eye of the captain at the same time as taking a wicket and a batsman for chances to turn the order around if he is to make an impact as a player one day.
But capturing the eye of the selectors is more complicated.
There were many who improved last season, for example James Anderson who plays surely in the first test even if Stephen Harmison declares for fit and bowls like the wind in the nets.
Anderson took 32 first-class wickets at 33 runs each to gain a place.
Chris Tremlett only took 29 at the same average, but both have had their highs and can expect more from these.
Shah&#39;s or Bopara&#39;s games at Asgiriya Stadium may only be a matter of opinion.
Choice can make or break a man&#39;s career, or it can make little difference.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, Gareth Batty played in every Test and did well in the first few, taking 5 wickets and a useful 40 runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, struggling to establish himself at the same time, who rose to prominence. and despite scoring a double hundred against Australia in Australia, he may still be underrated.
The likelihood is that Graveney, Vaughan and Moores, after further discussion in today&#39;s session at Asgiriya Stadium, will follow their self-preservation instincts and favor Shah&#39;s more experienced over the exuberance of the young Bopara.
There are arguments for both.
In Shah&#39;s favor is his brilliant and valuable debut Test of early &#39;88 in Bombay, 32 first-class hundreds to just 6 for Bopara, who, at 22, is seven years younger, and has an excellent record against spin bowling. .
But Shah made just ten runs in his two outings in May against the West Indies in the test at Lords, his Middlesex home, and that caused an immediate pushback from the selectors when Vaughan claimed his place for the next match, appearing to have taken of his batting something of élan that in Bombay.
By contrast, the Essex team have joie de vivre in spades.
He has a crush on nothing on the cricket ground and his attitude was summed up as when he flipped his car at a showroom for England&#39;s car sponsor Volkswagen.
He suffered minor injuries and, presumably shock, but the first thing he did was pull out his Vodafone (sponsored, of course) and call out to Alastair Cook, his teammate who was watching in the distance, to say excitedly: &quot; Did you see that?&quot;.
Bopara is the better player, he&#39;s including his slippery pass for effects on his plays that seem to satisfy him, as he hits with confidence and skill.
Choosing the right man is one thing, choosing the best time is another.
Perhaps that is the true art of selection.
My inclination would be to give Bopara his chance, which is not to say Shah won&#39;t excel, as the tea leaves suggest, he is the one playing here this weekend.
Buses bring refugees back to work - and the fight against Al-Qaeda
The first buses carrying Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday, expelling exiles who ran out of cash, without visa extensions and those who hoped the city would return to normality.
Some had even returned to fight the militants who had driven them from their homes.
At the Mansour bus station, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official government convoy of a dozen buses, the terminal was full of Syrian and Jordanian refugees who had returned by private transport.
&quot;I decided to go to Syria after many doctors were killed in Baghdad,&quot; says Sabah al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
&quot;I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I have read in the newspapers about what happened in Baghdad and that it is safe now.&quot;
&quot;They say the Mahdi army has stopped killing people,&quot; he says, referring to the Shi&#39;ite militia of religious militant Cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, who has ordered his troops to halt temporarily.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shi&#39;ite and a teacher in the Sunni area of Amariyah, returned with his two children because it was impossible to renew his visa in Syria as the regime does not want Iraqis working in their country.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariyah phoned him to say that a US-allied force helped drive al-Qaeda out of its stronghold west of the capital, urging him to return.
One of the new arrivals from Jordan was a Sunni and Shiite tribal chief who had been driven from his home in Sleikh north of Baghdad by a grenade attack after he urged citizens to rise up against al-Qaeda.
He had come to fight.
&quot;Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they had started an anti-Al-Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my comrades.&quot;
&quot;That&#39;s why I came back today,&quot; said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many said they were drawn by the growing calm in the capital since US troops entrenched groups of armed &quot;concerned citizens&quot; working cooperatively with the US military to defend their neighborhoods.
But many said they had returned because of the denial of visas and lack of money in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have settled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, a 51-year-old father of three, gave voice to the suspicion common among exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, called on the Syrian government to impose visa restrictions on refugees to force people to come back.
More than two and a half million people believe they have fled the country because of sectarian death gangs.
&quot;We were fine until al-Maliki visited Syria and urged the government to stop issuing visas to Iraqis, to force them to return to Iraq,&quot; the Sunni said.
&quot;I can&#39;t believe in a government that supports the criminals who burned down my house after I left it.&quot;
Part of the reason for the cessation of violence is that Sunnis have been expelled from Shiite areas and vice versa, easing the tension.
There are fears that a sudden wave of refugees will spark sectarian tensions anew and start fighting.
