Venus: Earth&#39;s twin brother.
Despite its atmosphere not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that until now had not been considered. The European probe &quot;Venus Express&quot; discovered lightning in the atmosphere and eddies at the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades now, researchers had suspected that lightning might exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, lightning strikes from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California at Los Angeles to the scientific journal &quot;Nature&quot;.
According to the famous Urey-Miller origin-of-life model, lightning caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the building blocks of life.
This is not the case on Venus: if there were ever to be life there, it would have to be in an early stage of evolution,&quot; explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and temperatures of 500°C reign on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
&quot;Possibly Venus is an &#39;evil&#39; twin of Earth, but it&#39;s still a twin,&quot; Russell said.
The main objective of the &quot;Venus Express&quot; mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth due to its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since there were no special missions since the 1990s, only for the investigation of this planet, the launch of &quot;Venus-Express&quot; in November 2005 was a very important step for the investigation of Venus.
The latest research results, which will be presented in many &quot;Nature&quot; articles, according to the researchers&#39; opinion, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
&quot;This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had previously assumed,&quot; the ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers also discovered a faster rotating cloud vortex in the south polar region.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the Earth&#39;s high atmospheric layers at the poles, as described by a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Institute for Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as big.
This planet, also called the morning star or evening star, orbits the Sun for almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not closely resemble Earth, scientists assume that both planets formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets, water had agglomerated that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated in the universe.
Whereas on Earth carbon dioxide had turned into carbon stones, on Venus it makes up most of the atmosphere.
