They are not the wooden boxes.
Whoever associates the terms Sweden and wooden box thinks of Ikea, but does not think of Andy Warhol.
Or if?
Today the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that hangs over Warhol&#39;s list of works.
Most of the ninety-four &quot;type&quot; Brillo-Boxes on this list are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper &quot;Expressen&quot; cast doubt on the authenticity of Andy Warhol&#39;s 1968 Brillo-Boxes a few months ago, the Moderna Museet in Stockholm carried out internal investigations and came to disappointing conclusions: the six &quot;Brillo-Boxes &quot;, which the ex-director of the museum Pontus Hultén gave to the Moderna Museet, are false, and almost a hundred of the other &quot;Stockholm type&quot;, which are in circulation in the international art market, turn out to be as well.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first &quot;Brillo-Boxes&quot; in New York, he painted the wooden boxes red, blue and white, with the same sample that they had boxes of &quot;Brillo&quot; soap powder.
According to Warhol, hundreds of Brillo-cardboard boxes were exhibited at the 1968 exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet. These were not made by Warhol (because of the expense), but were brought directly from the &quot;Brillo&quot; cardboard factory.
They were not works of art, but specimens (which were only objects) on display.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed some wooden Brillo-boxes to be produced in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Modern Museet.
Witnesses of those times now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as original &quot;Brillo-Boxes&quot; of the &quot;Stockholm type&quot; authorized by Andy Warhol.
At auction some of them were bought for more than 100,000 dollars.
The problem is that after the famous director of the museum Pontus Hultén made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left him were produced and exhibited.
But actually, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in Saint Petersburg.
At this time Warhol had already been dead for 3 years.
Lars Byström, the head curator of the Moderna Museet, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three privately owned Swedish ones that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. First their tight plates were printed and ground and then they were painted in oil with the brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the prints from the year 1990 shows that the paint was applied with a roller without directly printing the tight plates. In addition, it is not about oil painting, but about acrylic painting.
&quot;These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and must be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol Brillo-Boxes,&quot; says Lars Nittve, the director of Moderna Museet, adding that if the &quot;Andy Warhol Art&quot; Authentication Commission in New York will not come to any conclusion, Moderna Museet will classify these six boxes as copies/exhibits&quot;.
Already in July, the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these &quot;serious accusations&quot; in which they are boxes of soap powder.
But from that moment there everything remained in absolute silence.
